<!--
  APIM policy for the "CliquePix API v1" - applies at the "All operations"
  scope on that API (NOT the global / "All APIs" scope).

  HISTORY OF RATE-LIMIT REMOVAL (most recent first):

  2026-05-05 (incident #6 — orphaned op-scope policies declared in bicep/apim/main.bicep):
    User reported the red "Sign in failed" banner on Android after rebuilding
    the APK. Diagnosis took three escalating steps: (a) clear app data on
    device — didn't help (the rate-limit counter is keyed on JWT subject =
    user oid, so reinstalling the same user can't reset it); (b) Azure App
    Insights — backend `auth_verify_success` events were firing fine, no
    server-side exceptions, but no `requests` row matched the URL filter
    (filter wrong, but the absence-of-exception was the signal); (c) shipped
    a one-line `[AUTH-SIGNIN-FAIL]` debugPrint in
    auth_providers.dart:174-180 that prints the runtimeType, message, and
    (for DioException) status + body. Captured trace showed
    `DioException [bad response]: 429` with body
    `{statusCode: 429, message: "Rate limit is exceeded. Try again in 1
    seconds."}` on /api/auth/verify.

    Audit at all four APIM scopes (the Phase 0+A script audits operation
    scope but the prior cleanups stopped at API/Product). Found six
    operation-scope <rate-limit-by-key> policies on cliquepix-v1:
      - auth-verify        : calls=30 / renewal-period=60 (THIS bit the user)
      - upload-url         : calls=10 / renewal-period=60
      - catch-all-delete   : calls=30 / renewal-period=60
      - catch-all-patch    : calls=30 / renewal-period=60
      - catch-all-post     : calls=30 / renewal-period=60
      - catch-all-put      : calls=30 / renewal-period=60
    All keyed on JWT Subject (CIAM oid). 30 calls/60s is too tight for the
    app's actual sign-in retry pattern — the 5-layer Entra refresh defense
    + verify-in-background + AuthInterceptor 401 retry + a few user retries
    can blow past 30/min for one user in seconds.

    The bigger surprise: these policies were declared in bicep/apim/main.bicep at the
    repo root (lines 1247-1322 pre-fix). The 2026-04-29 cleanup deleted them
    in live APIM but a subsequent bicep deploy re-introduced them. The fix
    therefore had to touch BOTH source-of-truth (bicep) AND live APIM:
      Phase A: edit bicep/apim/main.bicep — remove the 6 apis/operations/policies
               resources, replace with explanatory comment block.
      Phase B: az rest DELETE on each of the 6 .../operations/{op}/policies/policy
               URLs. Each operation falls through to API-scope (clean).
      Phase C: sleep 90 + `az apim api update --protocols https` to flush
               Developer-tier in-memory counters and force gateway pod refresh.
    Verified: sign-in lands on Events screen post-fix; backend probe of
    /api/auth/verify returns 401 (canonical UNAUTHORIZED), not 429.

    OPERATIONAL LESSONS:
      1. The Phase 0+A audit script in BETA_OPERATIONS_RUNBOOK.md §2 audits
         live APIM. It DOES NOT audit IaC. Augment with:
           grep -nE 'apis/operations/policies' bicep/apim/main.bicep
         Any match needs to be checked for rate-limit-by-key in the inline
         policy XML.
      2. bicep/apim/main.bicep is the source of truth for ALL APIM resources,
         including operation-scope policies. This file (apim_policy.xml)
         only covers the API scope. The two are partially redundant — the
         API-scope policy is duplicated between this file and bicep
         line 1147. A future cleanup should consolidate to one source.
      3. The `[AUTH-SIGNIN-FAIL]` debugPrint at auth_providers.dart:174-180
         was the difference between days of guesswork and 60-second triage.
         It stays in the codebase as a permanent diagnostic.

  2026-04-29 (incident #5 — the one this comment is about):
    A brand-new test user hit the same 429 on their FIRST upload attempt
    even though this file was clean. Audit at all four APIM policy scopes
    found <rate-limit calls="5" renewal-period="60" /> AND
    <quota calls="100" renewal-period="604800" /> on the "starter"
    PRODUCT-scope policy — APIM's default scaffolding from when the
    service was first provisioned, never touched. New users auto-subscribe
    to "starter" and got slammed at 5 requests/min on first sign-in. The
    fix was to PUT a base/-only policy on the starter product. The lesson:
    when diagnosing a 429, audit ALL FOUR APIM policy scopes — global,
    product, API, operation — not just the API scope. This file only
    covers the API scope; cleaning it does not clean the others.

  2026-04-27 (incidents #1-4 — the original mass cleanup):
  rate-limit-by-key was removed from this policy after four consecutive
  user-blocking failures in beta:
    1. Original 120/min limit was easily exceeded by normal usage
       (5-layer Entra refresh defense, 30s feed polling, avatar SAS
       regeneration on every list/detail handler).
    2. Bumping to 300/min did not help; the Developer-tier in-memory
       counter cache appears to persist stale state across policy edits.
    3. Bumping to 600/min and bypassing critical paths still produced
       429 responses on a first-attempt upload (verified via
       APIM "RateLimitExceeded" metric).
    4. The same first-upload 429 reappeared on a follow-up attempt.

  Abuse protection now comes entirely from the application layer:
    - JWT bearer-token validation (every endpoint)
    - Event / clique membership check (every endpoint that accepts an
      event_id or clique_id)
    - User Delegation SAS (5-minute expiry, scoped to a single blob
      path; client cannot read or list)
    - Orphan cleanup timer (every 15 min) deletes pending uploads
    - Per-user video count cap (PER_USER_VIDEO_LIMIT, enforced in
      backend/src/functions/videos.ts)

  If real abuse risk emerges post-beta, the right response is:
    - Move APIM off Developer tier (Standard v2 has a distributed
      rate-limit cache and an SLA), THEN
    - Add per-user upload-frequency caps at the Functions layer where
      we control the logic and can debug it
    - Configure Azure Front Door WAF for genuine bot traffic patterns

  Do NOT re-add rate-limit-by-key OR <rate-limit> OR <quota> at ANY
  APIM scope without first migrating off APIM Developer tier. The
  6-incident history is documented reproducibly above; repeating it
  would be a regression.

  TIER NOTE: the prohibition above stands for ALL tiers, not just
  Developer. Per Microsoft's own docs ("Limit call rate by key"),
  rate limiting at APIM is "never completely accurate" on any tier
  because of the distributed throttling architecture. Classic tiers
  use sliding-window; v2 tiers use token-bucket. Migrating from
  Developer to Basic v2 (~$525/month) buys an SLA and slightly more
  burst-friendly bucket math, but does NOT make a too-tight limit
  generous. Prior versions of this comment said "Standard v2 has a
  distributed cache" — that's folkloric and isn't in Microsoft's
  docs. The right precondition for re-introducing rate-limit-by-key
  is LOAD-TESTING the limit against actual traffic patterns, not
  tier upgrade.

  Source of truth: this file (API scope only). For the other three
  scopes, the source of truth is the live APIM service — audit them
  with the Phase 0+A script in docs/BETA_OPERATIONS_RUNBOOK.md §2.

  Deploy this file via az rest PUT against the management API policy
  URL with a JSON body of the form:
    { "properties": { "format": "rawxml", "value": "<contents of this file>" } }

  An Azure Monitor metric alert ("apim-429-detected") fires on any APIM
  429 within 5 minutes; if it fires, run the Phase 0+A audit before
  doing anything else.
-->
<policies>
    <inbound>
        <base />
        <cors allow-credentials="false">
            <allowed-origins>
                <origin>https://clique-pix.com</origin>
                <origin>http://localhost:5173</origin>
            </allowed-origins>
            <allowed-methods preflight-result-max-age="3600">
                <method>GET</method>
                <method>POST</method>
                <method>PUT</method>
                <method>PATCH</method>
                <method>DELETE</method>
                <method>OPTIONS</method>
            </allowed-methods>
            <allowed-headers>
                <header>*</header>
            </allowed-headers>
            <expose-headers>
                <header>x-request-id</header>
            </expose-headers>
        </cors>
    </inbound>
    <backend>
        <base />
    </backend>
    <outbound>
        <base />
    </outbound>
    <on-error>
        <base />
    </on-error>
</policies>
